Question 1.¶

(25 points)

There are three types of coins which have different probabilities of landing heads when tossed:

Type A coins are fair, with probability 0.5 of heads

Type B coins are bent and have probability 0.6 of heads

Type C coins are bent and have probability 0.9 of heads

Suppose I have a drawer containing 5 coins: 2 of type A, 2 of type B, and 1 of type C. I reach into the drawer and pick a coin at random. Without showing you the coin I flip it once and get heads (i.e. event D). What is the probability it is

  • type A (i.e. $P(H = A|D)$)?

  • Type B (i.e. $P(H = B|D)$)?

  • Type C (i.e. $P(H =C|D)$)?

Fill out table below with your answers.

Step1:prior knowleges

The sample space of B is {a,a,b,b,c}, so the probability to pick up an A Type coin $P(H=A)=2/5$, so as $P(H=B)=2/5$, $P(H=C)=0.2$

hypothesis prior likelihood posterior
H P(H) P(D|H) P(H|D)
A 0.4
B 0.4
C 0.2

Step2: fill out the specific probabilities when different coin type is selected

hypothesis prior likelihood posterior
H P(H) P(D|H) P(H|D)
A 0.4 0.5
B 0.4 0.6
C 0.2 0.9

Step3: get P(D)

$ $

$P(D) = P(head\ of\ observe)$

$= area\ of\ the\ shadow\ of\ the\ probability\ space$

$= \frac{0.5\times 2 + 0.6\times 2 + 0.9}{5}$

= 0.62

Step4: now calculate the shrinked probability of observed a Head given certain coin type.

$P(H|D)=P(H)\frac{P(D|H)}{P(D)}$

hypothesis prior likelihood posterior
H P(H) P(D|H) P(H|D)
A 0.4 0.5 0.3326
B 0.4 0.6 0.3871
C 0.2 0.9 0.2903

Question 2. (25 points - Written)¶

Consider the following dataset of four rows and three features (Malicious, Viagara, Meet) with class labels (ham and spam). Suppose we see a message having these features M5 = (Malicious = yes ,Viagara = no ,Meet = yes ), What is the probability that it is a spam or ham? Using Naive Bayes algorithm.

S.No Malicious Viagara Meet class
M1 yes yes yes spam
M2 no no yes ham
M3 yes no yes spam
M4 no yes no ham
M5 yes no yes ?%

first, calculate the prior knowledge of labels spam & ham

$given\ P(class=spam)=0.5, P(class=ham)=0.5 $

$and\ P(Malicious=yes) = 0.5, P(Viagara=yes) = 0.5, P(Meet=yes) = 0.75$

$P(spam|X=M5)$

$ = P(spam|yes,no,yes)$

$=\frac{P(spam)P(yes,no,yes|spam)}{P(yes,no,yes)}$

$=\frac{P(spam)\times P(Malicious=yes|spam)\times P(Viagara=no|spam)\times P(Meet=yes|spam) + 1}{P(Malicious=yes)\times P(Viagara=no)\times P(Meet=yes) + 2}$

$P(ham|X=M5)$

$ = P(ham|yes,no,yes)$

$=\frac{P(ham)P(yes,no,yes|ham)}{P(yes,no,yes)}$

$=\frac{P(ham)\times P(Malicious=yes|ham)\times P(Viagara=no|ham)\times P(Meet=yes|ham) + 1}{P(Malicious=yes)\times P(Viagara=no)\times P(Meet=yes) + 2}$

$ $ since the equations have the same part of factor: $\frac{1}{P(Malicious=yes)\times P(Viagara=no)\times P(Meet=yes)+2}$ $ $

$\therefore P(spam|X=M5)\varpropto P(spam)\times(=|)(=|)(=|)+1$

$\varpropto{2/4\times2/2\times1/2\times2/2+1}$

$=1.25$

$\therefore P(ham|X=M5)\varpropto P(spam)\times(=|ham)(=|ham)(=|h)+1$

$\varpropto{2/4\times0/2\times1/2\times1/2+1}$

$=1$

$\therefore$ M5 has a $\frac{1.25}{1.25+1}=55.6\%$ probability to be spam, and has a 44.4% probability to be ham.

Question 3.(30 points - Written)¶

Use the below gradient descent algorithm to find the x value that minimizes the function $f(x) = 6x^{2}_{1} 3x_1x_2 + 2x^2_2$ .

Choose the starting point as $(x^{(0)}_1 , x^{(0)}_2 ) = (2,3)$ and use the $_k$ as 0.1 ans as 0.0001

Consider the following gradient descent algorithm (which is a variant of the directional search algorithm) that aims to find the x value that minimizes the function f(x).

Perform only 3 iterations of this algorithm and report the values of $(x_1, x_2)$ after performing gradient descent each time

$\because f(x) = 6x^{2}_{1} 3x_1x_2 + 2x^2_2$

$\therefore\frac{\partial f(x)}{\partial x_1}=12x_1-3x_2+2x_2^2\ \ ,\ \ \frac{\partial f(x)}{\partial x_2}=6x_1^2-3x_1+4x_2$

$\therefore\nabla f(x^{(k)})=[\frac{\partial f(x)}{\partial x_1}, \frac{\partial f(x)}{\partial x_2}]$

$\because\nabla f(x^{(k)})>\epsilon=0.0001\ and\ \eta_k=0.1$

$then,\ x^{k+1}=x^{k}-0.1\times[\frac{\partial f(x)}{\partial x_1}, \frac{\partial f(x)}{\partial x_2}]$

Perform 3 iterations of gradient descent

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D
import numpy as np
import math
def f(x1, x2):
    return 6*x1**2 - 3*x1*x2 + 2*x2**2
def fx1(x1, x2):
    return 12*x1-3*x2+2*x2**2
def fx2(x1, x2):
    return 6*x1**2-3*x1+4*x2
def mold(px1, px2):
    return math.sqrt((px1 ** 2 + px2 ** 2))
x1,x2=-0.8, -0.9
print("%d | [%d,%d]" % (f(x1,x2), fx1(x1,x2), fx2(x1,x2)))
T1=np.array([2,-1.3,0.2,-0.8,-0.3])
T2=np.array([3,0,-1.4,-0.9,-1.1])
T3=f(T1,T2)

3 | [-5,2]

1 -1.3 0

3 -0.8 -0.9

# self-check visualization
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
def numerical_gradient(f,P):
    grad = np.zeros_like(P)
    for i in range(P[0].size):
        grad[0][i] = fx1(P[0][i], P[1][i])
        grad[1][i] = fx2(P[0][i], P[1][i])
    return grad
lx1,rx1,r1=-1.5,2,0.2
lx2,rx2,r2=-1.5,3,0.3
x = np.arange(lx1, rx1+r1, r1)
y = np.arange(lx2, rx2+r2, r2)
X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)
X = X.flatten()
Y = Y.flatten()
grad = numerical_gradient(f, np.array([X, Y]))
plt.quiver(X, Y, grad[0], grad[1])
T1=np.array([2,-1.3,0.2,-0.8,-0.3])
T2=np.array([3,0,-1.4,-0.9,-1.1])
T3=f(T1,T2)
plt.plot(T1,T2,T3)
plt.xlim([lx1*1.2, rx1*1.2])
plt.ylim([lx2*1.2, rx2*1.2])
plt.xlabel('x1 label')
plt.ylabel('x2 label')
plt.grid()
plt.show()

# visualization for a better learning rate
def gradient_decent(x1, x2, alpha=0.05, epsilon=0.0001, max_iter=10000):
    x1, x2 = 2, 3
    px1, px2 = fx1(x1, x2), fx2(x1, x2)
    md = mold(px1, px2)
    T1, T2, T3 = [], [], []
    cnt = 0
    convergence_cnt = 0
    while True:
        if md < epsilon:
            print("break when gradient vanished: %.6f<%.6f after %d times. " % (md, epsilon, cnt))
            break
        if cnt > max_iter:
            print("break when iterate %d times with gradient %.6f. " % (cnt, md))
            break
        if convergence_cnt > 5:
            print("gradient convergence detected. ")
            break
        T1.append(x1)
        T2.append(x2)
        T3.append(f(x1, x2))
        px1 = fx1(x1, x2)
        px2 = fx2(x1, x2)
        tmp = mold(px1, px2)
        if tmp > md:
            convergence_cnt += 1
        md = tmp
        x1 = x1 - alpha * px1
        x2 = x2 - alpha * px2
        cnt += 1
    return T1, T2, T3

# print(T1,"\n",  T2,"\n",  T3)
fig1 = plt.figure(dpi=200)
ax = Axes3D(fig1)
X1, X2 = np.mgrid[-1.3:2:40j, -1.4:3:40j]
Y = f(X1, X2)
ax.plot_surface(X1, X2, Y, rstride=1, cstride=1, cmap=plt.cm.coolwarm, alpha=0.5)
T1,T2,T3=gradient_decent(2,3,alpha=0.1)
ax.plot(T1, T2, T3)
T1,T2,T3=gradient_decent(2,3,alpha=0.05)
ax.plot(T1, T2, T3)
T1,T2,T3=gradient_decent(2,3,alpha=0.00001)
ax.plot(T1, T2, T3)
ax.set_xlabel('x1 label', color='r')
ax.set_ylabel('x2 label', color='g')
ax.set_zlabel('y label', color='b')
plt.show()

Question 4. (20 points - Written)¶

Find the eigen values and eigen vectors for the following matrix. $\left[ \begin{matrix} 2&5\\ -1&2\\ \end{matrix} \right] \tag{1}$

$ A\vec x=\lambda \vec x$

$\Rightarrow A\vec x - \lambda I \vec x = 0 $

$\Rightarrow (A - \lambda I) \vec x = 0 $

$\Rightarrow det(A - \lambda I) = \left|\begin{matrix} 2-\lambda&5\\ -1&2-\lambda\\ \end{matrix}\right| = (2-\lambda)^2 - (-1\times5) = 0$

$\Rightarrow \lambda^2 - 4\lambda + 9 = 0$

for $ax^2+bx+c=0,\ \left\{ \begin{aligned} x_1 = m+ni & \\ x_2 = m-ni & \\ \end{aligned} \right. $

$then\ \left\{ \begin{aligned} x_1+x_2 & = -\frac{b}{a} = 4 = 2m\\ x_1\times x_2 & = \frac{c}{a} = 9 = m^2 + n^2\\ \end{aligned} \right. $

$\therefore m= 2,\ n= \sqrt{5}$

$\therefore \lambda_1=2 + \sqrt{5}i,\ \lambda_2=2 - \sqrt{5}i \tag{2}$

eigen values: [2.+2.23606798j 2.-2.23606798j]

remember $ A\vec x=\lambda \vec x$

$\Rightarrow \left[\begin{matrix}2&5\\ -1&2\\ \end{matrix}\right]\left[\begin{matrix}x1\\ x2\\ \end{matrix}\right] = \lambda \left[\begin{matrix}1&0\\ 0&1\\ \end{matrix}\right] \left[\begin{matrix}x1\\ x2\\ \end{matrix}\right]$

$\Rightarrow \left[\begin{matrix} 2-\lambda&5\\ -1&2-\lambda\\ \end{matrix}\right]$ $\left[\begin{matrix} x1\\ x2\\ \end{matrix}\right]=0$

$\Rightarrow \left\{\begin{aligned} (2-\lambda)x_1 + 5 x_2 = 0\\ -x_1 + (2-\lambda)x_2 = 0\\ \end{aligned}\right. $

$\Rightarrow \frac{x_1}{x_2} = (2-\lambda)$

for $\lambda_1=2 + \sqrt{5}i$

$\frac{x_1}{x_2} = -\sqrt{5}i$

$\xi_1 = \left[\begin{matrix} x1\\ x2\\ \end{matrix}\right]=\left[\begin{matrix} -\sqrt{5}i\\ 1\\ \end{matrix}\right] \tag{3} $

for $\lambda_2=2 - \sqrt{5}i$

$\frac{x_1}{x_2} = \sqrt{5}i$

$\xi_2 = \left[\begin{matrix} x1\\ x2\\ \end{matrix}\right] = \left[\begin{matrix} \sqrt{5}i\\ 1\\ \end{matrix}\right] \tag{4} $
